      {
        "id": 3051538,
        "name": "Jeremy Holmes",
        "username": "Jeremy_Holmes",
        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/www.wineberserkers.com/jeremy_holmes/{size}/1146_2.png",
        "created_at": "2020-12-20T09:10:04.000Z",
        "cooked": "<p>Got called up for Dury duty today, checking in on a vertical of Rougeots. The 2007 was my pick as the best wine. The 2005 was the most ready, in fact it is superb right now. The 2006 needs more time.</p>\n<p><strong>2005 Coche-Dury Meursault Les Rougeots:</strong> Absolutely in the zone. Has a whiff of struck match, coupled with notes of almond butter and white peach. It is full and round, textured, layered and long. Whilst structural elements are taking a back seat it lacks no spine or vigour. Terrific wine.</p>\n<p><strong>2006 Coche-Dury Meursault Les Rougeots</strong>: Strong petrol reduction to the nose. With air there\u2019s sappy orchard fruits and smoke. It is dense and chewy with great build and intensity, The finish has something floral akin to honeysuckle.</p>\n<p><strong>2007 Coche-Dury Meursault Les Rougeots:</strong> Incredibly youthful. Some struck match along with the most pure white peach fruit. It is direct and dense, loaded with chalky dry extract. It is still very tight and linear and possesses fabulous length.</p>",
        "post_number": 1,
        "post_type": 1,
        "posts_count": 6,
        "updated_at": "2022-06-04T00:26:28.270Z",
